<!DOCTYPE article PUBLIC "-//NLM//DTD Journal Archiving and Interchange DTD v2.3 20070202//EN" "archivearticle.dtd"><article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" article-type="review-article"><?properties open_access?><front><journal-meta><journal-id journal-id-type="nlm-ta">Emerg Infect Dis</journal-id><journal-id journal-id-type="pmc">eid</journal-id><journal-title>Emerging Infectious Diseases</journal-title><issn pub-type="ppub">1080-6040</issn><issn pub-type="epub">1080-6059</issn><publisher><publisher-name>Centers for Disease Control</publisher-name></publisher></journal-meta><article-meta><article-id pub-id-type="pmid">9366610</article-id><article-id pub-id-type="pmc">2640094</article-id><article-categories><subj-group subj-group-type="heading"><subject>Research Article</subject></subj-group></article-categories><title-group><article-title>Vero cytotoxin-producing Escherichia coli O157 outbreaks in England and Wales, 1995: phenotypic methods and genotypic subtyping.</article-title></title-group><contrib-group><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Willshaw</surname><given-names>G. A.</given-names></name></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Smith</surname><given-names>H. R.</given-names></name></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Cheasty</surname><given-names>T.</given-names></name></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Wall</surname><given-names>P. G.</given-names></name></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Rowe</surname><given-names>B.</given-names></name></contrib></contrib-group><aff>Central Public Health Laboratory, London, United Kingdom.</aff><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><season>Oct-Dec</season><year>1997</year></pub-date><volume>3</volume><issue>4</issue><fpage>561</fpage><lpage>565</lpage><abstract><p>Vero cytotoxin-producing Escherichia coli O157 belonging to four phage types (PTs) caused 11 outbreaks of infection in England and Wales in 1995. Outbreak strains of different PTs were distinguishable by DNA-based methods. Pulsed-field gel electrophoresis best discriminated among strains belonging to the same PT, distinguishing six of the seven PT2 outbreak strains and both PT49 outbreak strains.</p></abstract></article-meta></front></article>